I had a similar store bought product for the Xbox 360, and didnt feel like shelling out the extra money for the Xbox One version. Be gentle, and hold the head of the joystick as you push the extender down. DO NOT just mash down until the part fits. If it feels like your print came out too small, don't force it! Print each stick extender individually
I ran these off on a Solidoodle 2 at .3mm layer height, brim and concentric fill.
Print this part upside down, and you won't need supports.
When I ran off more than one of these at a time, the part quality improved visually, but the fit of the final part was too loose. I will be revising this design at some point so that I can print two or more out at once without losing the snug fit required.
If your pieces do come out fitting loosely, you may have some luck putting something like paper towel, or some other thin material underneath to tighten it up.

description.text:
This is a standard part for any CO2 cutter /engraver. The mirror holder allows to install a 25 mm mirror and provide 90 degree reflection with adjustment capability. I have not tried it in a laser cutter yet, and I don't know if ABS plastic would work, because all mirror holders sold online are made of metal. I was told, provided the mirror is clean, it should not heat very much. The part can be cut from aluminum too, I think. But I'm not sure how to cut the main block on a 3-axis CNC router, I'll give it a try later.

description.text:
This is an OpenSCAD version of the excellent e-liquid mixer "The Harduisteeper" by PeterCo014:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1987389

The micro servo 9G model used is done by TheCase, with some slight modifications:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:29734

It is an amazingly effective and cheap mixer for two e-liquid bottles (30ml to 50ml). It works even with 100% VG mixes.

I had a bunch of "el cheapo" Arduino mini 168 laying unused in a box, so an adaptation was needed to fit this model.
Having it in a parametric form also allows easy modifications and adaptations.
See the source code for comments on options.

Hardware needed:

  • Servo motor: Micro ("9G" type)
  • Ball bearing: 10mm ED, 3mm ID, 4mm width (can be adapted in source code)
  • Arduino Pro Mini 168 "Baite" (for example: https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1pcs-Pro-Mini-328-Mini-ATMEGA328-5V-16MHz-Free-Shipping/1432585134.html )
  • A micro-USB PCB (for example: https://www.aliexpress.com/item/10pcs-MICRO-USB-to-DIP-Adapter-5pin-Female-Connector-B-Type-PCB-Converter/32720363831.html )
  • A common cathode 5mm RGB LED
  • 3 resistors (2x470R + 1x560R)
  • 4x round foam pads for feets (37mm diameter), optional
  • Some screws (see source code header comments)

I included my quick adaptation of PeterCo014's original Arduino code.
My version has a pause between cycles and the movement speed is ramped progressively. Feel free to contribute modifications...
The comments are in french, as they were in the original file, but I can provide a translated version if needed.

Full printable, complete Z-axis solution for all lift platform 3D printer.

Platform holder due to the large size, to be printed and put together five pieces.
Central bracket length 180mm. While large pieces, but it fits easily into a standard 200 * 200mm printers.
Printed pieces should just slide into each other. Then, fixed screws. Because of the same self-positioning, assembling when you may need a bit of insistence.
Put your all the nuts into place formed. The PLA is too weak for metric threads.

Attention!
The PLA will melt very easily. Already at 40 ° C decreases the strength.

This is a small hand rake that my Dad wanted for his small strawberry garden. He had one that was just too big for the area he had planted. I thought tlalexander's design was great, so I used it for reference. I dont have solidworks, but designed this one in Autodesk Inventor.
It has a t-handle and hole in the T-handle to hang from a peg board on a nail. The T-handle was a request from my Dad to make it easy to dangle. The Center Prong is slightly longer to help dig just a little more of a trench. My 9-year old first saw this and thought it was a small back scratcher for him. I guess you could also use it for that, but it might not reach very far. I guess his request is on my list now. As intended, it has worked perfectly for a small garden area. Autodesk Inventor source file is also attached.

Please see my design for a Z axis brace for the Anet A2
The original acrylic part flexes too much but I did not want to print a whole new brace, the extruder part does not flex.
this brace screws into the frame using two t5 nuts and two 5mm x 12mm screws
I had to use longer screws for the z motor as the screws goes through this part, throught the acrylic part and into the motor.
this is my first part that had to be tight on sizes, this item may not look the best but works perfectly
I also changed my z coupler for a solid one

title: Spool axle for power drill winding

description.text:
I designed this to allow me to wind filament onto a spool using an electric drill or screwdriver. I used an M8 coach bolt and an M8 nut to attach the wedges to the spool and then put the end of the bolt into my drill.

The spool_wedge_square.stl file has a recess for the coach bolt head and the spool_wedge_nut.stl file has a recess for an M8 nut. You could also use some M8 threaded rod with two nuts or an M8 bolt with a hexagonal head.

description.text:
This is a tool used for calibrating your extruder steps per mm. It does not require any calculations, just insert it into your extruder (based on wade's style) and feed filament through it at desired amounts and record.   
The short test is designed to let the user extrude and then cut the pieces from the end in order to measure their length.   
The long test allows the filament to be extruded and held in place while using calipers to check the exact length. The body of the tester can be marked (or cut notches into it with a razor like I did) to indicate lengths.

Print out either the short or long calibration test and insert it into the bottom of your extruder, like you would your hot end.   
For the long test, extrude plastic into the sheath and record the length for later calculations. Use a razor blade or a marking device to indicate lengths.  
For the short test, mark or cut lengths of filament as you extrude them past the length of the tool. It is used as a reference point past the tip of the device.
